VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A short-lived biweekly children''s magazine featuring comics, puzzles, and celebrity interviews, known for its colorful design.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Pizzazz** was a short-lived biweekly magazine for children featuring comics, puzzles, and celebrity interviews, among other things. The magazine was published by Marvel Comics from 1977 to 1979.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pizzazz''s content catered to children of both genders, and included articles on diverse topics like music, movies, and television shows. The magazine was known for its colorful design, including hand-drawn illustrations and collages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of Pizzazz''s most popular features was the "Pizzazz Posterzine," a pull-out poster featuring photos and interviews with celebrities of the time, which young readers could hang up in their bedrooms.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While Pizzazz''s publication run was brief, the magazine left a lasting impression on its readers. The magazine helped launch the careers of a number of comic book artists and writers, including Jim Salicrup, Jo Duffy, and Eliot Brown.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, Pizzazz is remembered fondly as a unique piece of children''s publishing history, combining comics, celebrity interviews, and colorful design into a distinctive package.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Plain Truth
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
