INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A defunct monthly martial arts magazine from the US, covering various topics such as style profiles and training techniques, popularizing kung fu in the 1970s and 1980s.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Inside Kung Fu was a monthly magazine in the United States that covered various topics related to the martial arts, including style profiles, training techniques, and interviews with prominent martial artists. The magazine was in circulation from 1973 to 2009.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Inside Kung Fu was first published in 1973 by Rainbow Publications, which was also known for its publication of Black Belt magazine, another martial arts-focused magazine. During the 1970s and 1980s, Inside Kung Fu played an important role in popularizing the martial arts in the United States, particularly kung fu.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine featured style profiles, interviews with prominent martial artists, and training techniques for students of all levels. Over the years, Inside Kung Fu became a popular resource for practitioners of the martial arts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content of Inside Kung Fu was divided into several sections, including "Features," "Training," "Interviews," and "News." The "Features" section focused on various aspects of the martial arts, including the history and philosophy of various styles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "Training" section provided readers with techniques for improving their skills in various areas of the martial arts, including forms, sparring, and weapons training. The "Interviews" section featured interviews with prominent martial artists, including Bruce Lee and Jackie Chan.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "News" section provided readers with information about upcoming martial arts events and competitions, as well as news about the development of the martial arts in various countries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Inside Kung Fu had a dedicated readership among practitioners of the martial arts, with a circulation of approximately 100,000 copies at its peak. The magazine was known for its in-depth coverage of various martial arts styles, as well as its comprehensive training tips.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Inside Kung Fu received several awards for its content, including the Black Belt Hall of Fame Award for "Magazine of the Year" in 1993 and 1998.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Inside Kung Fu played an important role in the popularization of the martial arts in the United States during the 1970s and 1980s. The magazine''s in-depth coverage of various styles and its comprehensive training tips helped practitioners improve their skills and understand the broader context of the martial arts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, Inside Kung Fu is remembered as an important resource for practitioners of the martial arts, particularly kung fu. Its legacy lives on through various online resources and martial arts communities, which continue to discuss and analyze the techniques and philosophies.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

