VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A quarterly magazine published between 1958 and 1978 that focused on promoting and displaying abstract art covering work from emerging artists as well as established figures.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## It is. A Magazine for Abstract Art' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'It is. A Magazine for Abstract Art, also known simply as It is., is a quarterly magazine dedicated to abstract art. It was first published in 1958 by artist, poet and editor, Robert Indiana. The magazine was published until 1978 when its last issue was released.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'It is. was one of the most influential art magazines of the 1960s. The magazine aimed to provide a platform for abstract art and to promote its significance in the contemporary art world. It featured work from emerging abstract artists as well as established figures in the art world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine placed a strong emphasis on the visual presentation of abstract art. Its minimal layout and design approach favored the use of white space, sans-serif typeface, and a limited color palette.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Contributors to It is. included some of the most significant artists, writers, and thinkers of the time, such as Ellsworth Kelly, Ad Reinhardt, and Frank Stella. It also published works of criticism, poetry, and philosophy.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, It is. remains a significant artifact of the period in which it was published and has been featured in various art exhibitions and publications. The magazine is recognized for its contribution to the abstract art movement and continues to be a point of reference for contemporary art scholars and enthusiasts.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Jazz Review
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Jazz Review', N'the-jazz-review', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A now-defunct quarterly magazine dedicated to jazz music and culture, renowned for its intellectual approach and contributions from prominent jazz writers and musicians.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Jazz Review was a quarterly magazine that was first published in New York City in 1958. The magazine was founded by Nat Hentoff, a renowned jazz historian, author, and critic, and was published until 1961.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Jazz Review was dedicated solely to jazz music and its culture. The magazine provided extensive coverage of jazz music''s history, reviews of albums, concerts and festivals, interviews with prominent jazz musicians, and essays on jazz criticism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its publication period, The Jazz Review remained a prestigious forum for jazz musicians and intellectuals. The magazine featured articles by renowned jazz writers such as LeRoi Jones, Amiri Baraka, Martin Williams and Ralph Ellison. It also offered literary contributions from celebrated writers such as Jack Kerouac and Kenneth Rexroth.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Jazz Review was known for its sophisticated and intellectual approach to covering jazz music. The magazine was praised for its analytical tone, original research, and insightful reviews. The Jazz Review was considered as a premier journal for jazz scholarship and intellectual discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, The Jazz Review remains an important source for jazz music history and criticism. Many of its articles and essays have been reprinted in subsequent collections, and the magazine is recognized as one of the most influential publications in jazz music''s history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

