VALUES ( N'The Master Skier', N'the-master-skier', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine focused on cross-country skiing providing instruction, advice, and inspiration for skiers of all levels with high-quality photography and illustrations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Master Skier is a magazine dedicated to cross-country skiing. It was first published in the early 1980s by John Caldwell, a former Olympic skier and cross-country ski coach.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Master Skier provides readers with articles, instruction, and advice on a range of cross-country skiing topics. These include technique, training, gear, and nutrition. The magazine also features profiles of skiers, events, and destinations of interest to cross-country skiers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Master Skier is known for its high-quality photography and illustrations, with many of its images used to illustrate its articles and inspire readers. The magazine has also been recognized for its editorial excellence, winning several awards over the years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the popularity of alpine skiing, The Master Skier has enjoyed a loyal following among cross-country skiing enthusiasts. The magazine has been credited with helping to popularize the sport in North America, particularly in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Master Skier is published four times a year and continues to be a leading source of information and inspiration for cross-country skiers of all levels. With its focus on excellence and innovation, The Master Skier is a testament to the passion and commitment of cross-country skiing enthusiasts worldwide.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Matilda Ziegler Magazine for the Blind
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Matilda Ziegler Magazine for the Blind', N'matilda-ziegler-magazine-for-the-blind', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine providing information, entertainment, and advocacy for blind and visually impaired readers in print, audio, and digital formats.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Matilda Ziegler Magazine for the Blind is a magazine dedicated to providing information and entertainment for blind and visually impaired readers. The magazine was founded in 1907 by William Lightfoot Visscher and is named after Matilda Ziegler, a socialite who contributed funds to the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine features a range of content, including news, current events, and feature articles. It also includes poetry, fiction, and puzzles, as well as information on technology and products that can be helpful for visually impaired individuals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to traditional print editions, Matilda Ziegler Magazine for the Blind also makes its content available in audio and digital formats. This allows readers to access the magazine in a variety of ways that best suit their individual needs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has a long history of promoting the rights and interests of visually impaired individuals. It was one of the first magazines specifically designed for the visually impaired and has been recognized for its contributions to the field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Matilda Ziegler Magazine for the Blind is published by the eponymous Matilda Ziegler Foundation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to enhancing the quality of life for blind and visually impaired individuals. The magazine continues to be an important source of information, entertainment, and advocacy for this community.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Maximum Rocknroll
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Maximum Rocknroll', N'maximum-rocknroll', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A punk rock magazine covering DIY music, zines, and activism, with readers contributing reviews and content from around the world.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Maximum Rocknroll is a punk rock magazine founded in 1977 by Tim Yohannan. It was initially published monthly, but later changed to a smaller size and became a bi-monthly publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded in San Francisco and has been an influential voice in the punk rock scene for decades. Its coverage of punk rock music and culture has been described as comprehensive, with a strong focus on DIY ethics and political activism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to coverage of punk rock music, Maximum Rocknroll also provides information on punk rock zines, independent record labels, and touring bands. It has also been known for its record reviews, which are contributed by independent writers from around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Maximum Rocknroll has been praised for its politically progressive content and its commitment to promoting marginalized voices in the punk rock community. It has also been criticized for its adversarial approach to mainstream culture and for perceived elitism within the punk rock scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the challenges faced by print publications, Maximum Rocknroll continues to be published on a regular basis and remains an influential voice in the punk rock community. Its dedication to showcasing underground and DIY punk rock culture has made it an important resource for punk rock fans worldwide.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Meatpaper
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Meatpaper', N'meatpaper', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine dedicated to exploring the cultural, ethical, and environmental implications of meat consumption through essays, art pieces, and unconventional recipes.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Meatpaper is a magazine founded in 2007 by Sasha Wizansky and Amy Standen. The magazine is dedicated to exploring the intersections between meat and culture, with a focus on the ethical, environmental, and social implications of meat consumption.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine features a mix of content, including essays, interviews, and art pieces, as well as recipes that emphasize alternative meat sources like insects and plant-based proteins. Its editorial tone is described as playful and irreverent, with a strong sense of humor.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Meatpaper gained a cult following in the food world for its provocative content and unconventional approach to meat. The magazine has been described as an "anti-foodie" publication that challenges mainstream assumptions about food and food culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity, Meatpaper faced financial struggles in its later years and ceased publication in 2011. However, its impact on food culture has endured, with its innovative approach to meat and food culture influencing a generation of writers and chefs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In recent years, Meatpaper has been revived as an online publication, and some of its original content has been republished in the book "Meatpaper: A Book of Essays, Stories, and Recipes." The magazine''s legacy as a pioneer in the field of food journalism and culture criticism remains strong.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Mechanix Illustrated
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Mechanix Illustrated', N'mechanix-illustrated', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine dedicated to DIY technology, product reviews, and expert advice for inventors and engineers, with an editorial focus that shifted over time with changes in technology and popular culture.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Mechanix Illustrated was a magazine dedicated to DIY technology, published from 1928 to 2001. The magazine was founded by Joseph J. Flynn and first published by Modern Mechanix Publishing Company.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine featured a mix of articles, including technical how-tos, product reviews, and profiles of inventors and engineers. One of its most popular features was "The Question Box," where readers could submit questions and receive expert advice.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Mechanix Illustrated was especially popular during the 1940s and 1950s, when technological innovations and the post-war economic boom fueled interest in DIY technology. The magazine''s coverage extended beyond cars and mechanics to encompass topics like home improvement, electronics, and science.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine''s editorial focus shifted along with changes in technology and popular culture. In the 1960s and 1970s, for example, it featured articles on counterculture technologies like psychedelics and personal credit cards.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Mechanix Illustrated ceased publication in 2001, due in part to declining circulation and increased competition from online and digital media. Nevertheless, its legacy as a pioneering publication in the field of DIY technology and innovation remains strong, and its archives continue to be a valuable resource for historians and researchers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Media Life Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Media Life Magazine', N'media-life-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A former trade publication covering advertising, TV, radio, and the internet industries, particularly known for its coverage of innovative ad campaigns and emerging trends.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Media Life Magazine' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Media Life Magazine was a trade publication focused on the media industry. The magazine was founded in 1999 by Gene Ely, who had previously served as editor at Adweek and TV Guide.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine covered a range of topics related to media, including advertising, television, radio, and the internet. Its content included news, features, and interviews with industry leaders.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Media Life Magazine was particularly known for its coverage of the advertising industry, with a focus on innovative ad campaigns and emerging trends in brand marketing. It also provided analysis of the television and radio industries, with a focus on programming and audience demographics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Media Life Magazine ceased publication in 2011, due in part to declining advertising revenues and increased competition in the media trade publication industry. However, its legacy as a valuable resource for media professionals and industry observers remains strong, with its archives continue to be a source of information about the evolution of the media industry in the late 20th and early 21st centuries.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Mediaweek
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
